        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "# Welcome back, James \uD83D\uDC4B\n\nIt's great to meet you. Five years of running experience, a solid 44-minute 10K under your belt, and you're doing the right thing by coming back carefully — that takes real discipline, and it shows in your recent training history. The consistency you've built over the past few weeks, even at short distances, is exactly the foundation we want to build on.\n\nBefore I lay out the full plan, I want to check in briefly: **how is the foot feeling right now, day to day?** Not just on runs — I mean first thing in the morning, after sitting for a while, that kind of thing. Your answer won't change the structure much, but it'll help me frame the guidance around the walking break protocol in a way that actually fits where you are.\n\nThat said, here's everything you need to get started.\n\n---\n\n# James's Return-From-Injury Training Plan\n**Generated:** March 2026\n**Goal:** Safe, progressive return to running after plantar fasciitis\n**Clearance:** Physiotherapist-cleared for 20 min easy running, no speed work, walking breaks if foot pain present\n\n---\n\n## \uD83E\uDDED Coaching Rationale — The Big Picture\n\nYour pre-injury VDOT of 46.5 tells us you have a strong aerobic engine. But plantar fasciitis is a load-management injury — the tendon and fascia need *graduated mechanical stress* to remodel and strengthen, not just rest. Coming back too fast is the most common mistake, and it's usually what causes the second flare-up.\n\nHere's the framework I've used to build this plan:\n\n- **Every run is easy pace** (5:24–5:58/km). Your physiotherapist has cleared easy running only, and frankly, easy running is where 80%+ of your aerobic adaptation happens anyway. There's no fitness to be lost by staying here right now.\n- **3 days per week maximum**, with rest or gentle cross-training between run days. This gives the plantar fascia 48+ hours to recover between loading sessions.\n- **20-minute cap on all runs** until you're cleared for more. This is a hard ceiling, not a target to hit every session.\n- **Volume progression stays at or under 10% per week**, with a deload every 4th week. This is non-negotiable for tendon health.\n- **Walking breaks are built in as a tool, not a fallback.** If foot pain appears mid-run, you walk. That's not failure — that's smart load management.\n- **No speed work** until your physiotherapist clears it. Threshold, interval, and repetition paces are off the table for now.\n\nYour current weekly volume is roughly **9–10 km/week** based on recent history. We'll build from there.\n\n---\n\n## \uD83D\uDCC5 Plan Structure — 8 Weeks\n\nThe plan has three phases:\n\n| Phase | Weeks | Focus |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Phase 1: Consolidation** | 1–3 | Lock in 3 runs/week, build run:walk ratio |\n| **Phase 2: Extension** | 4–6 | Gradually extend continuous running time |\n| **Phase 3: Foundation** | 7–8 | Establish a stable base for the next chapter |\n\n---\n\n## \uD83D\uDDD3️ Weekly Schedule Template\n\n| Day | Session |\n|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy run (with walk breaks as needed) |\n| **Thursday** | Easy run (with walk breaks as needed) |\n| **Saturday** | Long run of the week (still capped at 20 min for now) |\n| **Other days** | Rest, gentle walking, or low-impact cross-training (swimming, cycling — no impact) |\n\n---\n\n## Phase 1 — Consolidation (Weeks 1–3)\n*Goal: Establish 3 consistent run days per week. Foot response is the guide, not the clock.*\n\n### Week 1\n| Day | Session | Duration | Target Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tue | Easy run/walk | 15 min | 5:58/km | 4 min run / 1 min walk intervals |\n| Thu | Easy run/walk | 15 min | 5:58/km | 4 min run / 1 min walk intervals |\n| Sat | Easy run/walk | 20 min | 5:58/km | 4 min run / 1 min walk intervals |\n| **Weekly total** | | **~50 min** | | **~8.4 km est.** |\n\n> **Walk break protocol:** Use 4:1 run/walk as your default. If foot feels good through the whole run, note it — that's useful data. If any pain appears, drop to 2:1 or walk the remainder. No heroics.\n\n### Week 2\n| Day | Session | Duration | Target Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tue | Easy run/walk | 15 min | 5:58/km | 6 min run / 1 min walk intervals |\n| Thu | Easy run/walk | 18 min | 5:58/km | 6 min run / 1 min walk intervals |\n| Sat | Easy run/walk | 20 min | 5:58/km | 6 min run / 1 min walk intervals |\n| **Weekly total** | | **~53 min** | | **~8.9 km est.** |\n\n### Week 3\n| Day | Session | Duration | Target Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tue | Easy run/walk | 18 min | 5:58/km | 8 min run / 1 min walk intervals |\n| Thu | Easy run/walk | 18 min | 5:58/km | 8 min run / 1 min walk intervals |\n| Sat | Easy run/walk | 20 min | 5:58/km | 8 min run / 1 min walk intervals |\n| **Weekly total** | | **~56 min** | | **~9.4 km est.** |\n\n---\n\n## \uD83D\uDD04 Week 4 — Deload\n*Pull back to ~70% of Week 3 volume. This is where adaptation actually happens.*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Target Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tue | Easy run/walk | 15 min | 5:58/km | 6 min run / 1 min walk |\n| Thu | Rest or walk | — | — | Gentle 20–30 min walk if desired |\n| Sat | Easy run/walk | 15 min | 5:58/km | 6 min run / 1 min walk |\n| **Weekly total** | | **~30 min** | | **~5.0 km est.** |\n\n> Deload weeks aren't a step backward — they're when your tendons, fascia, and aerobic system consolidate the work you've done. Think of it as depositing the gains.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2 — Extension (Weeks 5–7)\n*Goal: Progress toward continuous 20-minute runs. Walk breaks become optional rather than scheduled — use them if needed.*\n\n### Week 5\n| Day | Session | Duration | Target Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tue | Easy run | 18 min | 5:45–5:58/km | Attempt continuous; walk if pain |\n| Thu | Easy run | 18 min | 5:45–5:58/km | Attempt continuous; walk if pain |\n| Sat | Easy run | 20 min | 5:45–5:58/km | Attempt continuous; walk if pain |\n| **Weekly total** | | **~56 min** | | **~9.7 km est.** |\n\n### Week 6\n| Day | Session | Duration | Target Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tue | Easy run | 20 min | 5:30–5:58/km | Continuous target |\n| Thu | Easy run | 20 min | 5:30–5:58/km | Continuous target |\n| Sat | Easy run | 20 min | 5:30–5:58/km | Continuous target |\n| **Weekly total** | | **~60 min** | | **~10.5 km est.** |\n\n### Week 7\n| Day | Session | Duration | Target Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tue | Easy run | 20 min | 5:24–5:58/km | Full easy pace range now available |\n| Thu | Easy run | 20 min | 5:24–5:58/km | Full easy pace range now available |\n| Sat | Easy run | 20 min | 5:24–5:58/km | Full easy pace range now available |\n| **Weekly total** | | **~60 min** | | **~11.0 km est.** |\n\n---\n\n## \uD83D\uDD04 Week 8 — Deload + Reassessment\n*Second deload. Also a natural checkpoint to reassess with your physiotherapist.*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Target Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tue | Easy run | 15 min | 5:45–5:58/km | Easy and relaxed |\n| Thu | Rest or walk | — | — | — |\n| Sat | Easy run | 20 min | 5:45–5:58/km | Easy and relaxed |\n| **Weekly total** | | **~35 min** | | **~6.0 km est.** |\n\n---\n\n## \uD83D\uDEA6 Pain Response Protocol\n\nThis is the most important table in this plan. Treat it like a traffic light.\n\n| What you feel | What it means | What to do |\n|---|---|---|\n| **No pain** | Foot is tolerating load well | Continue as planned |\n| **Mild awareness / 1–3/10** | Normal tissue response | Finish the run, monitor next 24 hrs |\n| **Moderate pain / 4–6/10** | Approaching your limit | Walk the rest of the session, rest next day |\n| **Sharp or worsening pain / 7+/10** | Stop immediately | Walk home, contact your physio |\n| **Pain worse the morning after** | Load was too high | Drop back one week in the plan, contact physio |\n\n> A useful rule of thumb: pain that settles within 24 hours after a run is generally acceptable. Pain that's *worse* the next morning is a signal to back off and check in with your physiotherapist.\n\n---\n\n## \uD83D\uDD11 Key Paces (For Reference)\n\nThese are your Daniels-derived paces based on your 44:00 10K (VDOT 46.5). **Only easy pace is in play right now.**\n\n| Zone | Pace | Status |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Easy** | 5:24 – 5:58 /km | ✅ Active |\n| Marathon | 4:44 /km | \uD83D\uDD12 Locked |\n| Threshold | 4:29 /km | \uD83D\uDD12 Locked |\n| Interval | 4:12 /km | \uD83D\uDD12 Locked |\n| Repetition | 3:57 /km | \uD83D\uDD12 Locked |\n\n---\n\n## \uD83D\uDCCB What Happens After Week 8?\n\nIf things go well — no significant flare-ups, pain consistently at 0–2/10, and your physiotherapist is happy — Week 8 is a natural point to:\n\n1. **Get a physiotherapist clearance review** — ask specifically about extending run duration beyond 20 minutes and reintroducing any quality work\n2. **Begin extending the Saturday long run** toward 30–35 minutes\n3. **Gradually increase weekly volume** toward 15–18 km/week over the following 4–6 weeks\n4. **Eventually unlock tempo and threshold work** — your 44-minute 10K fitness is still in there, and there's a real path back to it\n\nYou're not starting over. You're reloading.\n\n---\n\n## \uD83D\uDCAC One Last Thing\n\nYou've already shown something important in the last few weeks — you've been running consistently, at the right pace, without pushing through pain. That kind of discipline is genuinely harder than running fast, and it's what makes comebacks stick.\n\n**How does this plan feel to you?** Is there anything about the structure — the pacing, the schedule, the walk break approach — that you'd want to adjust before you get started?"
        }
